  "prompt": "Why didn't Balram (brother of Krishna) participate in the Mahabharat War?",
  "response": "According to the Mahabharata, Balrama (also known as Balarama or Baladeva) did not participate in the Kurukshetra War for several reasons:\n\n1. Neutrality stance: Balrama tried to maintain neutrality between the Pandavas and Kauravas, who were his close relatives.\n\n2. Attempted peace: Before the war, he tried to mediate and prevent the conflict, hoping to reconcile the two groups.\n\n3. Spiritual path: He was more inclined towards spiritual practices and did not want to engage in direct warfare.\n\n4. Relationship with both sides: He was equally attached to both the Pandavas and Kauravas. Krishna was closely aligned with the Pandavas, while Balrama had a good relationship with Duryodhana.\n\n5. Divine plan: Some interpretations suggest that his non-participation was part of the larger divine plan for the war.\n\nWhen the war became inevitable, Balrama went on a pilgrimage, effectively removing himself from the conflict. He trained both Bhima and Duryodhana in mace fighting, but chose not to take sides during the actual war.\n\nAfter the war, he did not show any significant anger or resentment towards the outcome, maintaining his philosophical and detached approach.",
